import java.io.*;  // Import Input and Output Streams classes for reading & writing files (FileInputStream / FileOutputStream) but also Socket class java_43924_SocketServer_A03 provides methods to connect a socket with another device on the network, bind it onto an endpoint address in server side as well...etc etc  => IOException is thrown if there are no more bytes available at source or sink
import java.net.*;  // ServerSocket and Socket classes for creating servers & clients connection => BindException (if port not free), UnknownHostException when the hostname of a socket cannot be resolved to an IP address, NoRouteToHost exception thrown if there is no route in network that matches specified criteria
  
public class SimpleHTTPServer {  // Server will run until it receives 'exit' command from client. It does not handle close operations by clients due the simplicity of this example and just keeps server running to accept more connections later...etc etc => interrupt() is called when receiving a specific signal or event on an InputStream (like Socket accepting new connection, reading request)
    public static void main(String[] args){  // Main method where we define our socket client & its related operations.  => BufferedReader/BufferedWriter to read and write from the network buffer => ServerSocket for creating server side which listens on a specific port until it gets an incoming connection...etc etc
        try {    // Try-catch block used here as IOException is thrown if there are no more bytes available at source or sink.  When exception happens, we can handle that gracefully ie., by using catch and finally clause => close the socket (client), stream & file input/output streams when done with operation
            ServerSocket serverSock = new ServerSocket(12345); // Creating a TCP Socket at port 67890 for serving requests.  => BindException if an attempt to bind failed is made on this address, exception will be thrown due the simplicity of our example and we only want socket server operational until client attempts connection
            System.out.println("Server started."); // Display message when sever starts operation ie., listening at port 12345  => interrupt() if interrupted by user or system while waiting for a request from any source (client/server) => finally block to ensure that socket is always closed in case of exception
            Socket clientSock = serverSock.accept(); // Accepts incoming connection when there're no new requests received till now, blocking if none are available and makes the call thread sleep until it gets a request from another source (client/server) 
  
           PrintWriter out =new PrintWriter(clientSock.getOutputStream(), true);// Get an output stream to write into socket connection with client ie., sends response back at server side, will not block unless there are no more data left for sending => BufferedReader in case of reading from network buffer or input
           BufferedReader in = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader (clientSock.getInputStream())); // Get an input stream to read requests sent by client ie., can't write until the server has response back at this point, will not block unless there are no more data left for reading from socket connection 
  
           String request;// Holds incoming string message => BufferedReader/BufferedWriter used here if we have to send and receive large chunks of text (like HTML content) or binary files. In simple example these two fields won't be needed as the server only handles GET requests, hence no data is read into them before sending back a response
  
           // Keep looping until client sends 'exit'. When that happens we break out to main method and close socket connection (server).  This will stop all threads in this example. It's always good practice when writing server applications with sockets for real world scenarios, it should handle error cases gracefully as well:
           while ((request = in .readLine()) != null){ // Read a line from client => BufferedReader/BufferedWriter used here if we have to send and receive large chunks of text (like HTML content) or binary files. In simple example these two fields won't be needed as the server only handles GET requests, hence no data is read into them before sending back a response
             System.out.println("Received: " + request); // Print out what client sent => BufferedWriter used here if we have to send large chunks of text (like HTML content) or binary files and also write string from this point onwards with our server side, will not block unless there is no more data left for writing.
             out .println("Hello World!"); // Send back a line at client ie., receives request => BufferedWriter used here if we have to send large chunks of text (like HTML content) or binary files and also write string from this point onwards with our server side, will not block unless there is no more data left for writing.
           }  // End while loop which runs until client sends 'exit'. This handles TCP/IP connection between two devices by reading & sending messages to one another over network at high level (TCP) and then terminates the connections when user types "Exit" from console or application tab in browser...etc etc.
  
           // Close out stream, inputstream object after done using them => BufferedWriter/BufferedReader used here if we have read large chunks of text content back to client at server side and also write string for this point onwards with our closing socket connection operation by the user or system when they close their browser tab in web page application. 
           out .close(); // Close Printwriter, after writing data is finished => Socket used here will auto-cleanup resources once done using them (input & output streams) ie., server side and client's end of socket operation completion by the user or system when they close their browser tab in web page application.
           clientSock .close(); // Close input stream, after reading data is finished => Socket used here will auto-cleanup resources once done using them (input & output streams) ie., server side and client's end of socket operation completion by the user or system when they close their browser tab in web page application. 
           System.out.println("Connection closed."); // Display message to notify that connection is now finished with this client => ServerSocket used here will auto-cleanup resources once done using it as server side and after all requests are handled by the above loop (read & written operation) at end of program if not manually stopped
   }  catch(IOException e){// Catching IOException in case any error occurs while reading/writing to socket or other I/O related operations. => Finally block used here so that resources will be always closed when needed and no longer being accessed by anything else (like client connection) at end of program if not manually stopped
           System.out.println("Error: " + e); // Display error message back for the user or system to see what went wrong while executing this code => Finally block used here so that resources will be always closed when needed and no longer being accessed by anything else (like client connection) at end of program if not manually stopped
       } finally {// This part runs regardless whether an exception was thrown in try clause. It's a place where you put operations to cleanup all the resource, such as file handlers or database connections that were opened and need closing after use by any thread (both started from main method). In this case server side also close down its resources once it’s done
           System.out.println("Closing connection."); // Display message for user/system to see when the client has disconnected successfully => Socket used here will auto-cleanup resource if not manually stopped in previous try block, and finally块用于关闭所有已打开的资源以便于后续使用。
           } 
       System.out.println("Server Stopped."); // Display message to user/system when the server has indeed finished its operations before shutting down (either due end of program or other reasons). In this case also auto-cleanup resources like file handlers, database connections and sockets if not manually stopped in previous try block
    }  catch(Exception e){// Catch all exceptions. => Socket used here will close automatically because it is outside the specific code blocks (try/catch) that handle socket I/O operations at end of program when no exception occurred or was caught and handled before its exit to prevent resource leakage in multi-threaded environments
        System.out.println("An Error Occurred: " + e); // Display error message back for user / system  see what went wrong while executing this code => It's a catch all clause at the end of your try block, where you can handle any uncaught exception that occurred during execution
    }  
}//End Main Method. All java source files should have closing braces {}. This is not done in plain Java but by using IDE (Integrated Development Environment) which auto-closes curly {} brace when a line of code ends with it or if an error has been reported and the developer decided to fix that issue